Here’s the long awaited update on the GTI:
Since making the decision back in August to not push after SEMA ‘22, there simply hasn’t been progress on the GTI. Not going to lie about that. In August and September I didn’t even think about the GTI. I felt kind of burned out from it and was honestly enjoying the break. Spent a couple week back in Hungary with family and just enjoying being at home spending time not stressing.

Now between September-November, I started getting back to brainstorming. Spending more time thinking about widebody process for production with changing a couple things in the process and also the overall build plan with the GTI since now I have some more time on my plate. Around this time I also got word that @j.olau who has been the one handling all the 3D virtual work will be moving from Michigan to SoCal right by me. This means designing and working on the virtual files can now be done in person between us two which is amazing! One other thing around this time that I realized is that I will need somewhere to carry on working on the GTI since I will need to pull the motor, then start fabrication work on shaving the engine bay and cleaning up the interior to get ready for a full chassis respray(Something new im doing since I have more time now). I’m tapped out on my driveway and need a proper work area.

Fast forward to now. John is now here in SoCal which means we will getting back to the design work asap to get things finalized so the prototype process for the widebody can begin! With the rest of the car, there’s a good chance that I’ll have a place to be able to start on the rest of the work early 2023!

The puzzle pieces are coming together. It’s taken some time and patience but it’ll all be worth it. Can’t rush stuff like this and I’m glad I’ve realized that. Time for you guys to start seeing GTI progress again!

(Also enjoy these two photos of where the virtual work currently is. It’s about 90% complete. Lots of surfacing and refinement already completed with the virtual work. Now it’s the nitty gritty details and finalizing it)

Took the Borla catback exhaust I removed from the GTI and put it on the Golf. Also added the GTI carbon diffuser I removed since it was needed for the tips. Don’t need these on the GTI anymore so I figured I’d put them to use on my other mk6 hahah. Man does it sound good though. Perfect for a daily driver. The 5 cylinder is really such a great sounding engine even with simply just putting a catback on. Makes me excited for the Turbo 5 cylinder setup for the GTI. 

I’ve also added a couple other things from mk6 parts Ive had in storage including the cherry LED tails and the roof rack which both were the first mods I did to the GTI about 7 years ago. It’s all coming full circle lol. Next step, bagging it using the air suspension that I removed from the GTI since the GTI is getting coilovers 🤘🏻#vw #mk6 #golf

And that’s a wrap for 2022! It’s been a crazy year and one I won’t forget. I’ve taken some decent risks, failed at some things, success at other things and have overall learned alot. From continuing the widebody process on the GTI to my family trip back to Hungary to acquiring a second Trabant, it’s been quite the year. Nonetheless the past year has been the hardest and most mentally tough year of my life yet. It has really beat me up mentally but from that I’ve learned and hope to put certain things into effect this next year because of going through what I have this past year. There’s certain things I didn’t accomplish this year like completing the GTI to reveal but it simply wasn’t meant to be yet. Can’t rush things like that no matter how much pressure there is from the people watching along. I’m ready to see what doors open in 2023 and what I can do! Let’s get it👊🏻👊🏻 #letsgoNewYear

~ I’ve been wanting to make content around Trabants for awhile. I know content about Trabants wont be as popular as content about my GTI and that was expected. The views and likes and popularity is not what’s important about it and it will never be. The importance is the meaning behind the car. The true love for the car and creating the content of it to share. Some might think it’s just a weird old car or lame since it’s not the typical car you’d own or let alone want to modify and I totally get that. That’s where the love and meaning for certain things come in. That meaning is the deep childhood rooted obsession since when I was told about them from my parents and saw them in visiting back to Hungary as a kid. If I wasn’t Hungarian or if my father didn’t have one in his family growing up, I wouldn’t have this same attachment for these cars. I’m so glad I do though. As cliché as this sounds, It’s not just a weird, unique car that I think would be cool to own… it’s truly apart of me and sharing/making content about trabants/building them is something I’m just truly excited to share with you all 🖤 #ObessionForTrabants

Update on the shaved bay. Been making headway on removing all the seam seal, unnecessary brackets and grinding seams. Starting to look really cool already. Will be continuing the grinding and cleaning up the overall bay and also moving onto the rain tray area which what I will be doing to that hasn’t been done on the mk5/mk6 platform before. The past month has been wild. I’ve torn the GTI down to a bare chassis and have been cleaning up the chassis. Starting the shave bay process, removing any unnecessary things like brackets or all the threaded studs, etc. I’ve gotta say it’s been a lot of work so far getting it to this point. Lots of cutting, grinding and just plain hard labor. It’s been cool seeing what I’ve been able to do these past few weeks and watch myself getting faster and faster with whatever I’m doing. Phase 1 of getting down to a bare chassis is completed. Phase 2 of chassis cleanup is in process. Phase 3 will be starting the engine build and mock up😎 #vwgti #mk6 #racecarbuild

Raintray be gone! 😂If you’re familiar with the Mk5/6/7 chassis, you’d know that the rain tray is huge and hides the strut towers. Given that I’m going a clean and minimal setup, I’ve deleted the rain tray exposing the strut towers. It looks so much better already! For structural support since the rain tray is gone, a tubular strut brace will be put in place connecting the strut towers. 🤘🏻 #vwgti #mk6 #custombuild

Removed the OEM seat brackets as they would be a limiting factor with setting up the proper seat position. With doing custom tubular seat mounts that the seats side brackets can directly attach to, it’ll allow the seat to be positioned much lower and further back in comparison to the factory seats mount/bracket setup. Having the seat lower is beneficial as for one it lowers the center of gravity and also sets up my position with the pedal box better as the goal is to have the pedals be on horizontal plane to the bottom of the seat. Also glad I still have the @thestatusracing seats from the V3 setup. That way I don’t have to use my new ones for testing so they stay nice and clean. 🤘🏻 #vwgti #mk6 #custombuild
Got a lot still left to clean up in the engine bay but man does removing the rain tray open up and simplify the engine bay… 🤤 #vwgti #mk6 #custombuild #shavedbay

Turning radius may be one of the most overlooked aspects with widebody kits. With creating my own bodykit, this is something I wanted to make sure I didn’t skip out on. With how wide the kit will be, I needed to make sure I have proper scrub radius when turning, testing full lock, etc. This is important as this is a kit that will be sold and I want this kit to function not just look good. 

What I did was I put one of my work wheels on the front and then added 70mm of spacers to replicate where the wheel fitment will be with the kit. This is a 5” extension/poke per side in comparison to a stock GTI wheel. As you can see I did have to do some cutting. I had to cut off the lower fender mounting bracket and a part of the rocker. This was something simple to do and took a matter of 10min w/ shaving it down too. What I wanted to really test would be if the wheel makes heavy contact with the actual wheel well which would then require a notch in the wheel well. I didnt want customers of the kit to be required to have to notch their wheel well as it would intensive.

Fortunately, it all cleared! This means the potential wheel/tire specs will be 18x12 ET-20 with a 315/30/18 tire….. in the front. Insanely wide. Insane grip. On a golf. I’m excited.😅 #vwgti #mk6 #custombuild

Introducing @alkotoconcepts , my very own company for bodykits, aero and a lot more! This has truly been a long time coming……

This company is my life, my passion, my obsession. It’s my way to be creative and share what I create within the automotive world. This stems to the meaning of the word “Alkotó” which is a Hungarian translation for being creative or to be a creator. Meaning is everything for me.

This is my career. It’s my risk that I’m taking on creating a successful business and career for myself. It hasn’t been easy and it won’t be getting easier anytime soon but that’s where my determination to make this happen comes in. 

My goal is to create quality engineered products. Products that are designed beautifully, built with quality, and engineered to function. From bodykits, to aero components, to any other automotive parts I plan on producing, the quality, design and function will be the main focus.

 Go give @alkotoconcepts a follow to keep up to date with the journey! I will be making posts and content that I won’t share on my personal page and only on the company page so if you don’t want to miss out on anything, follow along!

I appreciate all you guys for the support over the years on my journey which has lead up to this point in time. It’s been insane. There has been some highs and some lows but the support from all of you has been constant which I can’t thank enough for!

Cheers to a new chapter🤘🏻#alkotoconcepts

Sincerely,
Steven

My dream is about to become a reality! I’ve partnered up with @largeformat3dprinter (MAKEiT 3D) to get the prototype of the bodykit made!  They will be utilizing their 2x4 large format printer using a Glass fiber nylon material to print the entire kit. This means entire panels can be printed in 1 to 2 pieces and they will be strong enough to have on the car for SEMA before making the production fiberglass parts later on.

The excitement is unreal and I’m truly looking forward to sharing this whole process with you guys! I can’t thank MakeIT enough for this amazing opportunity! Who’s ready to see some 3D printed panels! 😎🤘🏻 #vwgti #mk6 #customwidebody

It has been a wild ride so far that’s forsure. Excited to start having the physical prototype panels made within the next couple weeks. It’s about to get really real🫣 @alkotoconcepts // #vwgti #mk6 #customwidebody

The first 3D printed parts w/ @largeformat3dprinter ! Even though it’s not the bodykit panels yet, it’s super exciting as these are template pieces that will be mocked up against the car to show me where my fender widths will be as well as where the height of the radius sits. The goal was to create the ultimate mk6 kit so details like that matter a lot.

From spray foam in his drive way to SEMA, @typicalstevenn took a hands-on DIY approach to transform his basic mk6 GTI into a show-stopping masterpiece. Using spray foam to mold aggressive fenders reminiscent of the VW Motorsport Golf TCR, he then digitized the entire car in CAD to share his creation with the world. Every detail, from the cage to the pedal box, reflects TCR inspiration with a touch of his personality. The budget-inspired motorsport engine, based on a 5-cylinder 07K, blends the best of VW and Lamborghini, delivering over 500 horsepower.

Creating a bodykit from scratch is not a simple task especially when it needs to be brought from the virtual world to reality. @largeformat3dprinter truly made that possible with their 3D printing capabilities! 

The @alkotoconcepts Mk6 bodykit as you can see on my GTI is a complete 3D printed prototype that will be used to make molds so it can be produced and sold in fiberglass and carbon. The 3D printed panels allow you to make this workable prototype so you can not only see the design and testfit the part, but to also make molds from the prints and make production parts out of materials of your choice. 

Utilizing MakeIT’s 2x4 large format 3D printer, panels as large as the fenders were able to be printed in just one piece! The precision from the printer and the knowledge from the MakeIt team was simply top notch! Not only can you purchase a printer from them directly but if you’re looking for printing services, they offer that in house as well!

MakeIT played a fundamental role in the build process and I can’t thank them enough for giving me the opportunity to bring my bodykit to reality! 🙌🏻 @largeformat3dprinter // #3dprinting #vwgti #mk6 #racecar
